{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586178"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:27:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:27:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15071"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15071"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64414"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7759"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49846"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7665"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21222"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64414"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERenal cell carcinoma accounts for approximately 90% of kidney cancers in adults. Whilst the diagnosis of renal cell carcinoma used to be made on a collection of symptoms and signs, with today\u0027s imaging (both in terms of the technology and the increasing frequency of use), most of these tumour are now diagnosed as incidental findings. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the classic clinical triad associated with renal cell carcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone pain, cough, and dyspnoea","Fatigue, anorexia, and jaundice","Flank pain, haematuria, and palpable mass","Hypertension, headache, and sweating","Weight loss, fever, and anaemia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe classic triad of renal cell carcinoma consists of \u003Cstrong\u003Eflank pain, haematuria, and a palpable mass\u003C/strong\u003E in the flank region. However, this complete triad only occurs in approximately 10% of cases. When symptoms do occur, most patients present with just one or two of these symptoms. However, most renal cell carcinomas are diagnosed when they are found incidentally during an investigation undertaken for another reason. With these incidental discoveries, few of the patients have any symptoms that could be attributable to the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent various presentations that can occur but are not part of the classic triad: \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight loss, fever, and anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E are paraneoplastic manifestations; \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertension, headache, and sweating\u003C/strong\u003E may occur due to excess catecholamine production; \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone pain, cough, and dyspnoea\u003C/strong\u003E suggest metastatic disease; and \u003Cstrong\u003Efatigue, anorexia, and jaundice\u003C/strong\u003E are non-specific symptoms that can occur in advanced disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The classic triad of renal cell carcinoma is flank pain, haematuria, and a palpable abdominal mass, though this occurs in only 10% of cases","Renal cell carcinoma often presents late due to the kidney\u0027s location deep in the retroperitoneum","Most renal cell carcinomas are now discovered incidentally on imaging"],"references":["Rose TL, Kim WY. Renal Cell Carcinoma: A Review. JAMA. 2024 Sep 24;332(12):1001-1010. doi: 10.1001/jama.2024.12848. PMID: 39196544.","Mohammad A, McClintock C. Renal cell carcinoma--a great mimicker. Conn Med. 2007 Feb;71(2):81-4. PMID: 17393899.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49846"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15071"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21221"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21221"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8vJoVHoYLzwAutCgNLxq67QqAZl1rO.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8vJoVHoYLzwAutCgNLxq67QqAZl1rO.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":456,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49846"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T16:02:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T16:02:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7759"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64414"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urolo